ElementDescription: The NDAR Global Unique Identifier (GUID) for research subject
Subject ID how it's defined in lab/project
Date on which the interview/genetic test/sampling/imaging/biospecimen was completed. MM/DD/YYYY
Age in months at the time of the interview/test/sampling/imaging.
Notes: Age is rounded to chronological month. If the research participant is 15-days-old at time of interview, the appropriate value would be 0 months. If the participant is 16-days-old, the value would be 1 month.

ElementDescription: Sex of subject at birth
Notes: M = Male; F = Female; O=Other; NR = Not reported

ElementDescription: Form used/assessment name
Participant endorses worry about: Future
Participant endorses worry about: Own health
Participant endorses worry about: Other's health
Participant endorses worry about: Family well-being
Participant endorses worry about: Finances
Participant endorses worry about: Social relationships (relationships that are NOT romantic or sexual)
Participant endorses worry about: Intimate relationships (relationships that are romantic or sexual)
Participant endorses worry about: Work
Participant endorses worry about: School
Participant endorses worry about: Routine daily activities
Participant endorses worry about: Other (specify)
Frequency of worry: How often do you worry about (endorsed worry)?
Frequency of worry: Do you worry all day long?
Frequency of worry: Do you worry every day?
Frequency of worry: On average, how much of each day is occupied with excessive, unrealistic worries?
Notes: 0 = No time at all; 1 = Less than 1 hour each day; 2 = Between 1 and 3 hours each day; 3 = Between 3 and 8 hours each day; 4 = More than 8 hours of worry each day

ElementDescription: Distress due to worrying: How much distress does worrying cause you?
Notes: 0 = None; 1 = Mild; 2 = Moderate; 3 = Severe; 4 = Very severe

ElementDescription: Distress due to worrying: How upset or uncomfortable do you feel when you are worrying?
Notes: 0 = None; 1 = Mild (not too disturbing); 2 = Moderate (definitely disturbing but still manageable); 3 = Severe (very intense and disturbing); 4 = Very severe (incapacitating)

ElementDescription: Frequency of associated symptoms: Over the past week, how often did you experience these anxiety/GAD symptoms?
Notes: 0 = Not at all; 1 = Symptoms present 1 day; 2 = Symptoms present 1 to 2 days; 3 = Symptoms present 2 to 5 days; 4 = Symptoms present more than 5 days

ElementDescription: Frequency of associated symptoms: Do you have these anxiety/GAD symptoms every day?
Frequency of associated symptoms: On average how much of each day did you have one or more of these anxiety/GAD symptoms?
Notes: 0 = Not at all; 1 = Symptoms present less than 1 hour each day; 2 = Symptoms present 1 to 3 hours each day; 3 = Symptoms present 3 to 8 hours each day; 4 = Symptoms present more than 8 hours each day

ElementDescription: Severity and distress due to associated symptoms: Over the past week, on average, when you have had these symptoms, how intense were they?
Notes: 0 = Not present; 1 = Mild; 2 = Moderate; 3 = Severe; 4 = Very severe

ElementDescription: Severity and distress due to associated symptoms: How much distress did these anxiety/GAD symptoms cause you?
Notes: 0 = None; 1 = Mild; 2 = Moderate; 3 = Severe; 4 = Very severe

ElementDescription: Severity and distress due to associated symptoms: How upset or uncomfortable do you feel when you had these anxiety/GAD symptoms?
Notes: 0 = Not at all disturbed or uncomfortable; 1 = Not too disturbed or uncomfortable; 2 = Definitely disturbed an uncomfortable, but still manageable; 3 = Very intensely disturbed and uncomfortable; 4 = Incapacitated

ElementDescription: Impairment or interference in work functioning: How much do your anxiety/GAD symptoms interfere with your ability to work and/or carry out responsibilities at home?
Notes: 0 = No interference; 1 = Slight interference (but overall performance not affected); 2 = Moderate interference (but still manageable); 3 = Severe interference (causes substantial impairment); 4 = Very severe interference (incapacitating)

ElementDescription: Impairment or interference in work functioning: How much do your anxiety/GAD symptoms interfere with your ability to do things quickly and effectively?
Notes: 0 = No interference; 1 = Slight interference (but overall performance not affected); 2 = Moderate interference (but still manageable); 3 = Severe interference (causes substantial impairment); 4 = Very severe interference (incapacitating)

ElementDescription: Impairment or interference in work functioning: Are there things you are not doing because of your anxiety/GAD symptoms?
Impairment or interference in work functioning: Do your anxiety/GAD symptoms ever require you to take shortcuts or request assistance in order to get things done?
Impairment or interference in social functioning: How much do your anxiety/GAD symptoms interfere with your social life?
Notes: 0 = No interference; 1 = Slight interference (but overall performance not affected); 2 = Moderate interference (but still manageable); 3 = Severe interference (causes substantial impairment); 4 = Very severe interference (incapacitating)

ElementDescription: Impairment or interference in social functioning: Do you spend less time with your friends and relatives than you used to?
Impairment or interference in social functioning: Do you turn down requests or opportunities to socialize?
Impairment or interference in social functioning: Are there certain restrictions in your social life about where or how long you will socialize?
Generalized Anxiety Disorder Severity Scale Total Score
